<DOC><DOCNO> AP880519-0267 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-19-88 0201EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   05-19 0478</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0504</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Construction of single-family homes dipped inApril, the government has reported, providing evidence that highermortgage interest rates may be dampening building activity.   The Commerce Department reported Wednesday that single-familyhome building dropped 6.9 percent to a seasonally adjusted annualrate of 1.10 million units last month.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. imports of crude oil rose 24.1 percent inApril from year-earlier levels while total domestic productionregistered a 2.7 percent decline, a trade association said.   The American Petroleum Institute reported Wednesday in itsMonthly Statistical Report that U.S. imports of crude oil andpetroleum products averaged 7.04 million 42-gallon barrels daily inApril, up from 5.77 million barrels daily in April 1987.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Internal Revenue Service has refunded$55.9 billion to taxpayers this year, about one-eighth of thepersonal income taxes that were collected in advance in 1987.   The IRS said Wednesday that 65.1 million couples andindividuals, or 80.4 percent of the returns that have beenprocessed so far this year, qualified for refunds. The refundsaveraged $860.   The total number of refunds was up slightly, from 64.8 millionlast year. The amount refunded declined, from $56.1 billion, as didthe average, from $866.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   President Reagan's chief economic adviserpredicts there will be a loss of more than 600,000 jobs if Congressincreases the minimum wage from the current $3.35 to $4.65 an hourover three years.   Beryl W. Sprinkel, chairman of the president's Council ofEconomic Advisers, said in a letter released Wednesday to Rep.Thomas E. Petri, R-Wis., that job losses ``would be concentratedamong younger, less skilled and minority workers.''</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. steelmakers are prepared to file a waveof unfair trade suits against foreign competitors if the U.S.voluntary import quota plan is not extended, according to theleader of the domestic industry.   ``The American steel industry ... will not stand idly by andwatch ... import abuses which threw our companies into a five-yearbath of red ink,'' Thomas C. Graham, chairman of the American Ironand Steel Institute, said Wednesday.   Voluntary restraint agreements negotiated by the Reaganadministration with 31 foreign nations are due to expire inSeptember 1989.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Few youngsters are likely to answer ``actuary''to the question of what they want to be when they grow up, but anew book rates it as the best job of all.   Typical children's choices like doctor and astronaut ran farbehind less glamorous professions such as computer programmers,statisticians and parole officers in ``The Jobs Rated Almanac,''published by American References Inc. of Chicago.   Actuaries _ who interpret statistics to determine expectedpersonal losses _emerged No. 1 overall, as determined by thealmanac's criteria, which includes salary, stress, workenvironment, and job security.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>